abstract_one = """With funding from this pilot award, we aim to refine and evaluate our CandyCollect O2C microfluidic system, a lollipop-inspired device designed for patient-friendly saliva-based pathogen collection. CandyCollect, which has already garnered positive feedback from children and parents, captures a variety of microbes and performs on par with traditional diagnostic methods. However, the current manual process for transferring pathogens to rapid antigen detection tests (RADTs) is prone to errors and exposure risks. We developed the CandyCollect O2C system to automate pathogen elution and enable inline detection with RADTs, improving safety and convenience. Preliminary experiments with group A streptococcus (GAS) bacteria spiked into saliva have shown that O2C provides comparable or superior results to manual methods. However, the prototype is labor-intensive to assemble and not yet integrated with RADT kits. Our goal is to refine the CandyCollect O2C prototype to reduce hands-on time (≤ 5 min), minimize failure rates (≤5% among 30 devices), and ensure a low limit of detection (~105 colony forming units/mL). We will conduct a pilot usability study among minimally trained users, targeting a test difficulty rating of ≤3/10 and a ≥90% preference compared to conventional tests. Successfully achieving these milestones will position us to pursue larger clinical validation studies, medium throughput manufacturing, and multiplexed tests for multiple respiratory pathogens, ultimately leading to a device that enhances diagnostic accuracy and accessibility, particularly for children. This project has the potential to significantly improve human health by providing a safer, more user-friendly alternative to existing respiratory pathogen detection methods."""
a1 = ("Abstract 1", abstract_one)
